04733nam a22007095i 9781442661448DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20182014onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426614487 a10.3138/97814426614482doi  a(DE-B1597)497076  a(OCoLC)1046613824  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a781.62009462231 aSieburth, Stephanie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSurvival Songs :bConchita Piquer's 'Coplas' and Franco's Regime of Terror /cStephanie Sieburth. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Iberic00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Conchita Piquer’s Coplas as Psychotherapy -- tChapter One. Camouflage: The Psychology of Survival in Franco’s Spain -- tChapter Two. An Introduction to the Copla and Its Star Performer -- tChapter Three. Coping with Terror through Popular Music: “La Parrala” (“The Wine Lady”) -- tChapter Four. Paradise Lost: “Ojos verdes” (“Green Eyes”) as Ritual of Separation -- tChapter Five. “Tatuaje” (“Tattoo”), the Unburied Dead, and Complicated Grief -- tChapter Six. The “Other Woman”: “Romance de la otra” as Ritual of Marginalization and Disenfranchised Grief -- tChapter Seven. Reasserting Personhood through Popular Song: “Romance de valentía” (“Ballad of Bravery”) and “La Ruiseñora” (“The Nightingale”) -- tChapter Eight. When a Radio Song Is the Meaning of Life: Mending the Torn Fabric of Identity through Narrative, Music, and Interpretation -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow can a song help the hungry and persecuted to survive? Stephanie Sieburth’s Survival Songs explores how a genre of Spanish popular music, the copla, as sung by legendary performer Conchita Piquer, helped Republican sympathizers to survive the Franco regime’s dehumanizing treatment following the Spanish Civil War (1936–39). Piquer’s coplas were sad, bitter stories of fallen women, but they offered a way for the defeated to cope with chronic terror, grief, and trauma in the years known as the “time of silence.”Drawing on the observations of clinical psychotherapy, Sieburth explores the way in which listening to Piquer’s coplas enabled persecuted, ostracized citizens to subconsciously use music, role-play, ritual, and narrative to mourn safely and without fear of repercussion from the repressive state. An interdisciplinary study that includes close readings of six of Piquer’s most famous coplas, Survival Songs will be of interest to specialists in modern Spanish studies and to clinical psychologists, musicologists, and those with an interest in issues of trauma, memory, and human rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCoplaszSpainxHistory and criticism. 0aCoplaszSpainxPsychological aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular musiczSpainxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musiczSpainxPsychological aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266144840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442661448423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442661448.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK